<DOC><DOCNO> AP880708-0142 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-08-88 1328EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Heat     07-08 0298</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Greece-Heat,0308</SECOND><HEAD>Death Toll Reaches 31, Another 3,000 Go To Hospitals</HEAD><DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The death toll from a six-day heat waverose to 31 on Friday and officials said 111-degree temperaturessent more than 3,000 people to hospitals.   The government ordered Athens' 100 biggest factories to reducetheir emissions output by 30 percent to cope with high smog levelsover the city.   Hospitals nationwide remained on alert to handle smog and heatwave victims. The National Weather Service said the temperature inAthens reached 111 degrees Fahrenheit at 3 p.m.   ``The temperature will remain much the same tomorrow amd we'reexpecting it to start dropping on Sunday,'' said a weather servicespokeswoman.   The National Center for Emergency Help said 3,143 people went tohospital outpatient clincs with heat related problems and 558 werehospitalized, most of them with heart and breathing problems.   A spokesman for the center said six people died of heat strokeovernight. Coroner Nikos Benardis reported another 10 heat-relateddeaths, bringing the total for the past five days to 31.   ``Three of them were in their 80s and died of heart failure dueto dehydration, while the others had chronic illnesses that wereagggravated by the heat,'' Benardis told The Associated Press.   The soaring temperatures also forced several hundred people toseek refuge at a 15,000-seat, air-conditioned indoor sports stadiumin Athens' port city of Piraeus.   ``Many of them are pregnant women or couples with infants. Thereare some elederly people as well. They're coming in steadily,''said Panayiotis Kontozamanis, the stadium's director.   Government anti-pollution measures have failed to eliminate abrown smog mass that has plagued the city for years. Known as thenefos, the Greek word for cloud, the smog mass forms in the loweratmosphere on warm, still days.</TEXT></DOC>